In [51]:
df['Inspection Date']= pd.to_datetime(df['Inspection Date'])
df['Inspection Year']=df["Inspection Date"].apply(lambda x: x.strftime('%Y'))
df['Inspection Month']=df["Inspection Date"].apply(lambda x: x.strftime('%m'))
df['Inspection Year and Month']=df["Inspection Date"].apply(lambda x: x.strftime('%Y-%m'))

#Step 2.1
outer_list=[]
for a,b in enumerate(df2.columns):
    inner_list=[]
    if a>=11 and a<=26:
        inner_list.append(b)
        inner_list.append(df2[b].sum(axis = 0, skipna = True))
        outer_list.append(inner_list)
print(outer_list)
df_new=pd.DataFrame(outer_list)
df_new=df_new.rename(columns={0: "Violation Type", 1: "Count"})

Step 2.2 - For establishments with multiple inspections, how many reinspections does it take for an establishment to become compliant? Created a table where each row is the number of inspections a restaurant has had and the columns are the number of reinspections until the establishment becomes compliant.¶

In [67]:
tired=df2.sort_values(['Establishment ID','Inspection Date'], ascending=[True, True])
grouped=tired.groupby(['Establishment ID'])
In [68]:
uniqueval=df2['Establishment ID'].unique()
uniqueval.sort()
In [69]:
inspectionslist=[]
idlist=[]
rowlist=[]
for j in uniqueval:
    table=grouped.get_group(j)
    table=table[['Establishment ID','Dummy_Inspection','Inspection Date']]
    table=table.reset_index(drop=True)
    #table
    if(len(table)!=1):
        for i in range(len(table),0,-1):
            x=table.index[i-1]
            #if(table.iloc[x,1]==1):
                #break
            if(table.iloc[x,1]==0):
                if(x==0):
                    a=0
                else:
                    a=table.index[i-1] #+1
            elif(table.iloc[x,1]==1):
                break
        if(((len(table)-1))!=x):
            idlist.append(table.iloc[0,0])
            rowlist.append(a)
            inspectionslist.append(len(table))
        elif((((len(table)-1))==x) & table.iloc[x,1]==0):
           idlist.append(table.iloc[0,0])
           rowlist.append(a)
           inspectionslist.append(len(table)) 
#print(idlist,rowlist)

import plotly.express as px

fig = px.line(tabular, x='Inspection Year and Month', y='Dummy_Inspection', title='Percentage of Restaurants with at least 1 violation'¶

,labels={'Inspection Year and Month':'Date','Dummy_Inspection':'Percentage'})

fig.show()

The line graph shows us that the inspections are getting easier over time.

In November 2018 the Inspections seems to be the most lenient with only 30% of the restaurants with more than 1 violation.

It follows a pattern of having high number of violations during the months of July-August of each year

This could probably be because July-August is the peak season for travellers to come to the US, and in order to keep the restaurants in chec,k the inspections are strict and rigorous.

To display the trends I filtered the data according to what violation had a dummy as 1 and mapped it using plotly

After rigorous analysis I found a cluster of restaurants that did not comply for Proper hands washing near Shady Grove Rd and Frederick Rd

These factors can be due to lack of :-

1)Hand hygiene training.

2)Manager certification.

3)Hand washing supplies located at the hand sinks.

4)Management encouragement of hand washing.
